1
00:02:17,076 --> 00:02:18,744
Monsieur Rom...

2
00:02:25,125 --> 00:02:26,544
Opar.

3
00:02:27,545 --> 00:02:29,421
(INHALES DEEPLY)

4
00:02:29,505 --> 00:02:31,757
We found it.

5
00:02:40,182 --> 00:02:41,475
Captain Moulle?

6
00:02:46,230 --> 00:02:48,107
Form your lines.

7
00:02:48,482 --> 00:02:49,525
(GUNS COCKING)

8
00:02:55,823 --> 00:02:57,616
Maxims ready, sir!

9
00:03:03,372 --> 00:03:05,040
CAPTAIN MOULLE: Steady.

10
00:03:10,880 --> 00:03:12,464
Wait.

11
00:03:21,265 --> 00:03:22,391
Fire!

12
00:03:35,195 --> 00:03:36,322
(GUNFIRE STOPS)

13
00:03:43,078 --> 00:03:44,330
CAPTAIN MOULLE: Fall in!

14
00:04:38,217 --> 00:04:39,218
(YELLS)

15
00:04:40,177 --> 00:04:41,637
(MEN GRUNTING)

16
00:04:57,569 --> 00:04:59,196
Stand your ground!

17
00:05:15,754 --> 00:05:16,755
(GROANING)

18
00:06:11,810 --> 00:06:13,187
(GRUNTING)

19
00:06:18,609 --> 00:06:19,985
(CHOKING)

20
00:06:36,710 --> 00:06:39,171
Chief Mbonga, I presume?

21
00:06:40,172 --> 00:06:42,049
How do you know my name?

22
00:06:43,967 --> 00:06:45,677
You're the man I came to see.

23
00:07:02,694 --> 00:07:04,947
These are what you came for.

24
00:07:11,036 --> 00:07:12,913
What would you do for them?

25
00:07:14,665 --> 00:07:16,542
Whatever is necessary.

26
00:07:18,001 --> 00:07:22,631
There is one thing I desire
above all else.

27
00:07:23,507 --> 00:07:25,217
Bring it to me.

28
00:07:25,717 --> 00:07:28,095
Bring him to me.

29
00:07:28,720 --> 00:07:30,973
And you shall have your diamonds.

30
00:07:35,310 --> 00:07:37,187
All I need is a name.

31
00:08:14,558 --> 00:08:18,061
His Serene Highness,
King Leopold of Belgium,

32
00:08:18,228 --> 00:08:21,440
has extended an invitation
to Lord Greystoke

33
00:08:21,565 --> 00:08:25,485
to take a royal tour
of the Congo Free State

34
00:08:25,652 --> 00:08:28,113
to visit the schools
and churches he's built

35
00:08:28,655 --> 00:08:32,201
to acknowledge the success
of his anti-slavery initiatives

36
00:08:32,367 --> 00:08:34,620
and to open trade discussions.

37
00:08:35,204 --> 00:08:36,705
(WALNUT SHELLS CRACKING)

38
00:08:41,668 --> 00:08:46,173
Lord Greystoke,
let me explain the Africa situation.

39
00:08:46,840 --> 00:08:47,841
Mmm.

40
00:08:49,635 --> 00:08:52,471
King Leopold controls the Congo.

41
00:08:53,096 --> 00:08:54,973
He's defaulting on his loans,

42
00:08:55,140 --> 00:08:58,268
and needs a business partner
to fill the gap.

43
00:08:58,435 --> 00:09:01,146
Your invitation is a perfect opportunity

44
00:09:01,313 --> 00:09:04,149
for Her Majesty's government
to get involved.

45
00:09:05,108 --> 00:09:08,528
Consider the jobs we would create
for the poor natives of the Congo.

46
00:09:08,987 --> 00:09:10,614
- (SHELLS CLANKING)
- (GEORGE GROANS)

47
00:09:11,365 --> 00:09:13,867
And I thought the Civil War was long.

48
00:09:13,992 --> 00:09:16,286
Dr. Williams, you are a guest here.

49
00:09:16,453 --> 00:09:18,914
GEORGE: Prime Minister,
if you're not going to say it,

50
00:09:20,666 --> 00:09:21,875
allow me.

51
00:09:22,042 --> 00:09:24,836
You are Tarzan.

52
00:09:25,003 --> 00:09:28,173
Lord of the Apes, King of the Jungle.

53
00:09:28,340 --> 00:09:30,133
"Me Tarzan, you Jane!"

54
00:09:30,300 --> 00:09:32,344
Tarzan! Tarzan.

55
00:09:34,096 --> 00:09:36,890
King Leopold's inviting you
because you're a celebrity.

56
00:09:37,057 --> 00:09:39,768
He wants to show you
the schools and churches he built.

57
00:09:39,935 --> 00:09:42,312
You "ooh" and "ah"
in front of the newspapers,

58
00:09:42,437 --> 00:09:45,732
and he's validated
by Africa's favorite son.

59
00:09:46,775 --> 00:09:50,612
England pays his debts. We make money.

60
00:09:50,779 --> 00:09:53,282
- Ham sandwich. Easy.
- Hmm.

61
00:09:53,573 --> 00:09:56,285
So, Your Majesties,

62
00:09:56,451 --> 00:09:59,371
can we get this show on the road?

63
00:10:05,877 --> 00:10:06,878
(SLURPS)

64
00:10:15,053 --> 00:10:16,054
No.

65
00:10:16,221 --> 00:10:17,848
- No?
- For Heaven's sake, why not?

66
00:10:18,015 --> 00:10:20,475
Well, I've already seen Africa.

67
00:10:22,352 --> 00:10:23,437
And it's hot.

68
00:10:24,062 --> 00:10:26,565
Excuse me? Did you say "hot"?

69
00:10:30,068 --> 00:10:33,071
Please send my apologies
to His Serene Highness.

70
00:10:38,035 --> 00:10:40,579
And my name isn't Tarzan.

71
00:10:40,746 --> 00:10:42,706
It's John Clayton III.

72
00:10:42,873 --> 00:10:45,876
Son of John and Lady Alice Clayton.

73
00:10:46,043 --> 00:10:50,088
Fifth Earl of Greystoke,
member of the House of Lords.

74
00:10:57,095 --> 00:10:58,764
GEORGE: Mr. Clayton.

75
00:10:58,930 --> 00:11:01,433
Lord Clayton. My apologies.

76
00:11:01,600 --> 00:11:04,478
George Washington Williams.
Diplomatic envoy for the United States.

77
00:11:04,644 --> 00:11:06,938
- I was sent by President Harrison.
- JOHN: To do what?

78
00:11:07,105 --> 00:11:08,607
Join up with the Queen's emissary.

79
00:11:08,774 --> 00:11:12,110
America was the first country to recognize
King Leopold's claim on the Congo.

80
00:11:12,736 --> 00:11:15,072
You don't want to lose
your place at the trough.

81
00:11:15,238 --> 00:11:16,448
Look...

82
00:11:17,574 --> 00:11:20,452
I need your invitation to get in.

83
00:11:20,619 --> 00:11:22,996
I'm afraid my intentions aren't exactly

84
00:11:23,163 --> 00:11:25,332
what I expressed
to your government or mine.

85
00:11:27,626 --> 00:11:30,462
And what exactly
do you want, Dr. Williams?

86
00:11:32,339 --> 00:11:36,593
Leopold spent the last seven years
getting control of the Congo.

87
00:11:36,760 --> 00:11:39,221
He used up his entire fortune
building that railroad of his,

88
00:11:39,388 --> 00:11:42,224
then shut off access
to 99% of the country.

89
00:11:42,391 --> 00:11:43,350
Why?

90
00:11:43,517 --> 00:11:45,519
Because he wants to be
the first monarch in history

91
00:11:45,685 --> 00:11:48,146
who doesn't want people
to see his good deeds?

92
00:11:48,313 --> 00:11:49,981
I don't buy it.

93
00:11:50,607 --> 00:11:52,275
Tell me this, Lord Clayton.

94
00:11:52,442 --> 00:11:57,406
How does a bankrupt king
keep the whole of the Congo working?

95
00:11:59,991 --> 00:12:01,159
Slavery?

96
00:12:02,619 --> 00:12:05,831
I hope I'm wrong, but I need to know.

97
00:12:05,997 --> 00:12:08,959
And for the sake
of your friends back home,

98
00:12:09,126 --> 00:12:10,168
you do, too.

99
00:12:12,337 --> 00:12:16,383
Accept Leopold's invitation
and take me with you.

100
00:12:16,550 --> 00:12:19,010
You know Africa off the beaten path.

101
00:12:19,177 --> 00:12:21,638
The languages, the people, the customs.

102
00:12:22,347 --> 00:12:23,682
If we find anything amiss,

103
00:12:23,849 --> 00:12:28,728
then I need someone to tell the world
that they'll believe.

104
00:12:37,237 --> 00:12:39,030
I'll make all the arrangements.

105
00:12:39,197 --> 00:12:41,199
I'll see you in Liverpool.

106
00:12:48,373 --> 00:12:49,416
(EXHALES SHARPLY)

107
00:13:00,177 --> 00:13:01,761
(COWS MOOING)

108
00:13:12,397 --> 00:13:13,773
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

109
00:13:14,816 --> 00:13:16,193
JOHN CLAYTON Il: My family.

110
00:13:18,737 --> 00:13:21,448
I have done all I can to protect them.

111
00:13:25,327 --> 00:13:28,455
We have been surrounded by predators
since the shipwreck.

112
00:13:28,538 --> 00:13:30,081
(INFANT CRYING)

113
00:13:30,916 --> 00:13:32,792
The jungle consumes everything.

114
00:13:34,169 --> 00:13:38,256
It preys on the old, the sick,
the wounded, the weak.

115
00:13:38,423 --> 00:13:40,425
But never the strong.

116
00:13:44,095 --> 00:13:46,598
Today, I buried my Alice.

117
00:13:47,849 --> 00:13:49,768
My dear Alice.

118
00:13:52,187 --> 00:13:53,563
Now I fear for my child.

119
00:13:56,399 --> 00:13:57,776
God help us.

120
00:13:57,859 --> 00:13:58,860
(SNORTS)

121
00:13:59,069 --> 00:14:00,529
God help him.

122
00:14:00,612 --> 00:14:01,696
(DISTANT ROARING)

123
00:14:16,836 --> 00:14:17,837
(GRUNTS)

124
00:14:27,305 --> 00:14:28,306
(SCREAMING)

125
00:14:34,604 --> 00:14:35,814
(INFANT CRYING)

126
00:14:54,749 --> 00:14:56,293
(COOING)

127
00:15:05,510 --> 00:15:07,178
(SNARLING)

128
00:15:09,889 --> 00:15:11,349
(ROARS)

129
00:15:15,854 --> 00:15:19,733
JANE: The most dangerous beast
in Africa is so powerful,

130
00:15:19,899 --> 00:15:23,361
it can snap a crocodile's back
with a single bite.

131
00:15:24,529 --> 00:15:26,114
(WHISPERING)

132
00:15:26,197 --> 00:15:27,699
Anyone?

133
00:15:29,159 --> 00:15:31,202
MARY: Is it a hippopotamus?

134
00:15:31,369 --> 00:15:34,956
Yes! Precisely. Well done, Mary.

135
00:15:37,626 --> 00:15:38,627
Now,

136
00:15:38,793 --> 00:15:42,547
can anyone tell me
what my favorite bird sounds like?

137
00:15:43,590 --> 00:15:45,300
- Anyone?
- (WHISPERING)

138
00:15:49,721 --> 00:15:51,139
(MIMICKING BIRD'S CALL)

139
00:16:02,108 --> 00:16:03,652
BOY: How do you travel through the jungle?

140
00:16:03,818 --> 00:16:05,445
Why'd you leave the jungle?

141
00:16:05,570 --> 00:16:07,489
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

142
00:16:07,572 --> 00:16:08,573
BOY 2: Look at his hands!

143
00:16:09,574 --> 00:16:11,576
CHILDREN: Whoa!

144
00:16:12,619 --> 00:16:14,746
I grew up running on all fours.

145
00:16:15,580 --> 00:16:17,916
It changed the bone structure.

146
00:16:22,253 --> 00:16:24,506
BOY 3: Do you swing on things inside?

147
00:16:24,673 --> 00:16:26,800
Like, when you go upstairs?

148
00:16:26,966 --> 00:16:29,886
Oh, I never take the stairs.

149
00:16:30,095 --> 00:16:31,429
I usually take the curtains.

150
00:16:31,596 --> 00:16:32,681
BOY 3: Amazing!

151
00:16:33,556 --> 00:16:36,351
Is it true your mum was a monkey?

152
00:16:38,061 --> 00:16:40,063
Well, of course not.

153
00:16:40,230 --> 00:16:42,440
My mum was Alice Clayton.

154
00:16:46,111 --> 00:16:47,946
I can't wait to see Wasimbu again.

155
00:16:48,113 --> 00:16:49,531
- How many children would he have now?
- Jane.

156
00:16:49,698 --> 00:16:51,741
We know about Keko. She's what, four?

157
00:16:51,908 --> 00:16:53,660
- Everyone would have children.
- Jane.

158
00:16:53,827 --> 00:16:55,704
I mean, eight years
just feels like a lifetime!

159
00:16:55,870 --> 00:16:57,122
This isn't a holiday.

160
00:16:57,288 --> 00:16:59,457
How many corsets does a diplomat bring?

161
00:16:59,624 --> 00:17:01,418
I can't take you.

162
00:17:02,627 --> 00:17:04,546
- I say zero.
- Four.

163
00:17:05,296 --> 00:17:08,675
I suppose a British lady should faint
at least twice to justify the silly title.

164
00:17:08,842 --> 00:17:09,843
It isn't safe there.

165
00:17:10,009 --> 00:17:11,678
Of course it's not safe there, John!

166
00:17:11,845 --> 00:17:15,473
You take a nap in the wrong place,
you've got a 50-50 chance of being eaten.

167
00:17:16,683 --> 00:17:18,768
Ladies. Albert.

168
00:17:25,942 --> 00:17:28,820
You can't possibly still think
there is a danger, John.

169
00:17:32,031 --> 00:17:35,326
And you haven't spoken his name in years.

170
00:17:38,163 --> 00:17:39,497
Talk to me.

171
00:17:41,249 --> 00:17:43,501
Mbonga is not my concern.

172
00:17:44,127 --> 00:17:45,336
You are.

173
00:17:46,004 --> 00:17:47,922
We lost a baby.

174
00:17:48,089 --> 00:17:51,176
The last thing you need is more stress.

175
00:17:53,845 --> 00:17:55,263
Yes, well...

176
00:17:56,347 --> 00:17:58,057
Thank you for the reminder.

177
00:17:59,392 --> 00:18:02,228
Well, in case you forgot,
we both grew up there.

178
00:18:03,563 --> 00:18:05,982
So, perhaps I will fulfill your duties
for the Queen,

179
00:18:06,149 --> 00:18:07,358
and you can stay here

180
00:18:07,525 --> 00:18:10,028
hybridizing coconuts
and playing ping-pong.

181
00:18:12,614 --> 00:18:15,074
(SIGHS) I want to go home.

182
00:18:15,241 --> 00:18:16,367
This is our home.

183
00:18:19,287 --> 00:18:21,372
Trying to keep me here won't work!

184
00:18:21,581 --> 00:18:22,707
(OUTER DOOR SLAMS)

185
00:18:23,041 --> 00:18:24,042
(DOOR OPENS)

186
00:18:44,854 --> 00:18:46,356
(CHITTERING)

187
00:19:17,846 --> 00:19:18,847
(GROWLING)

188
00:19:25,937 --> 00:19:26,938
(SCREAMING)

189
00:19:27,981 --> 00:19:29,440
- (ROARING)
- (SCREECHING)

190
00:19:38,616 --> 00:19:39,617
(SCREAMING)

191
00:19:45,790 --> 00:19:46,791
(ROARING)

192
00:19:53,756 --> 00:19:54,966
(GROWLING)

193
00:20:08,438 --> 00:20:09,439
(GROWLS)

194
00:21:45,952 --> 00:21:47,328
JOHN CLAYTON Il: John, my son,

195
00:21:47,495 --> 00:21:50,415
you are the heir to Greystoke, our future.

196
00:21:53,084 --> 00:21:55,795
England is your home,
not this wretched place.

197
00:21:57,422 --> 00:21:58,423
If I don't survive,

198
00:22:00,925 --> 00:22:03,344
I pray that someone will save you.

199
00:22:38,838 --> 00:22:39,839
(GRUNTS)

200
00:23:00,610 --> 00:23:03,529
Promise me
you'll stay with the Kuba the whole time.

201
00:23:52,245 --> 00:23:54,122
(GEORGE LAUGHS)

202
00:23:54,205 --> 00:23:55,748
GEORGE: Not a chance, ma'am.

203
00:23:55,915 --> 00:24:00,169
A kick from one of these Walker Colts
is pretty nasty.

204
00:24:00,336 --> 00:24:02,421
As a matter of fact,
that's why they went out of style.

205
00:24:02,588 --> 00:24:05,716
Pretty little ladies like you
kept knocking themselves in the face.

206
00:24:05,800 --> 00:24:06,884
(JANE SCOFFS)

207
00:24:06,968 --> 00:24:09,846
I'll bet I could
hit that log over there, first try.

208
00:24:09,929 --> 00:24:11,055
Oh! (CHUCKLES)

209
00:24:15,518 --> 00:24:16,727
JOHN: Jane?

210
00:25:01,564 --> 00:25:04,192
He's known them since they were cubs.

211
00:25:17,121 --> 00:25:18,456
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

212
00:25:35,181 --> 00:25:36,974
MAJOR KERCKHOVER:
Force Publique, move aside.

213
00:25:37,141 --> 00:25:39,644
Force Publique, move aside!

214
00:25:41,229 --> 00:25:42,855
I want port of entry,

215
00:25:43,022 --> 00:25:45,775
I want port of disembarkation
for every passenger.

216
00:25:45,942 --> 00:25:47,485
Yes, sir. These are the last.

217
00:25:47,652 --> 00:25:49,987
- Sir.
- Thank you. Thank you.

218
00:26:05,336 --> 00:26:06,337
Excuse me, sir.

219
00:26:07,505 --> 00:26:08,673
The ledger.

220
00:26:08,839 --> 00:26:10,299
Yes, thank you.

221
00:26:16,180 --> 00:26:17,348
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWS)

222
00:26:32,196 --> 00:26:33,364
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

223
00:26:37,159 --> 00:26:40,037
MAJOR KERCKHOVER:
Gramophone, Mr. Rom's stateroom.

224
00:26:42,498 --> 00:26:43,582
ROM: Mr. Frum.

225
00:26:45,042 --> 00:26:46,669
Those crates go in the hold.

226
00:26:46,836 --> 00:26:50,798
Champagne? And music?
Your entire operation just fell apart.

227
00:26:50,965 --> 00:26:52,008
Have faith, Mr. Frum.

228
00:26:52,174 --> 00:26:54,051
Faith is for missionaries.

229
00:26:54,218 --> 00:26:55,469
He gave you the slip.

230
00:26:57,346 --> 00:26:59,390
MAJOR KERCKHOVER:
Make sure the rest goes down below.

231
00:27:00,808 --> 00:27:03,894
ROM: Our invitation
has been snubbed, Mr. Frum.

232
00:27:04,061 --> 00:27:05,813
They jumped ship further up the coast,

233
00:27:05,980 --> 00:27:08,149
and they are
on their own little tour home.

234
00:27:09,191 --> 00:27:12,945
So, from Boma up to here
will take me three days.

235
00:27:13,112 --> 00:27:16,073
I shall deliver Tarzan and return.

236
00:27:16,240 --> 00:27:17,867
A week's delay.

237
00:27:18,034 --> 00:27:20,536
You're in no position
to ask for anything, Mr. Rom.

238
00:27:20,703 --> 00:27:23,456
Your king's payment was due
three months ago.

239
00:27:23,622 --> 00:27:24,707
Yes.

240
00:27:27,835 --> 00:27:28,836
(BELL RINGING)

241
00:27:32,423 --> 00:27:35,760
I manipulated my firm
to keep this deal alive.

242
00:27:35,926 --> 00:27:37,178
You agreed
because you'll get stinking rich,

243
00:27:37,345 --> 00:27:38,429
so don't get trutty.

244
00:27:38,596 --> 00:27:39,847
Now, you must buy us more time.

245
00:27:40,014 --> 00:27:42,141
I already bought all the time...

246
00:27:42,308 --> 00:27:43,476
Look, it's really very easy.

247
00:27:43,642 --> 00:27:45,186
You sail out to the arriving fleet

248
00:27:45,353 --> 00:27:46,979
and tell them payment
must be made in Boma

249
00:27:47,146 --> 00:27:48,814
for security reasons.

250
00:28:06,916 --> 00:28:08,459
Opar had better not be a myth.

251
00:28:11,796 --> 00:28:14,882
Bring me the rest,
and you'll have your mercenaries.

252
00:28:15,049 --> 00:28:16,759
But if you fail to make good this time,

253
00:28:16,926 --> 00:28:19,595
my firm will go to the Belgian parliament
for compensation.

254
00:28:19,762 --> 00:28:21,263
Your king will lose this land,

255
00:28:21,430 --> 00:28:23,432
and who do you think he will blame?

256
00:28:23,599 --> 00:28:25,101
Leon Rom?

257
00:28:58,008 --> 00:28:59,385
Tarzan, you look funny.

258
00:28:59,677 --> 00:29:01,137
(CHUCKLES)

259
00:29:01,303 --> 00:29:03,681
(SPEAKING OTHER LANGUAGE)

260
00:29:04,098 --> 00:29:05,391
(LAUGHING)

261
00:29:18,779 --> 00:29:20,072
Wukonseeni!

262
00:29:20,239 --> 00:29:22,283
- Sangonini!
- Janey!

263
00:29:23,033 --> 00:29:24,869
- Sangonini.
- Ton moh nah nah ha lah.

264
00:29:25,369 --> 00:29:26,787
(ALL CHEERING)

265
00:29:27,037 --> 00:29:28,622
(ALL SINGING IN OTHER LANGUAGE)

266
00:29:33,544 --> 00:29:34,545
JANE: Keikoo.

267
00:29:36,422 --> 00:29:37,923
(BOTH SPEAKING OTHER LANGUAGE)

268
00:29:46,599 --> 00:29:47,600
(LAUGHS)

269
00:29:51,353 --> 00:29:52,354
- (SINGING STOPS)
- (ALL CHEERING)

270
00:29:57,902 --> 00:29:58,903
Wasimbu?

271
00:29:59,653 --> 00:30:01,405
Oh, my God!

272
00:30:05,201 --> 00:30:07,870
Janey Porter. Welcome home.

273
00:30:08,746 --> 00:30:10,331
(ALL CONTINUE SINGING
IN OTHER LANGUAGE)

274
00:30:17,505 --> 00:30:19,048
WASIMBU: As is custom,

275
00:30:19,215 --> 00:30:21,592
no one has entered until you returned.

276
00:30:30,559 --> 00:30:32,645
This is where Jane grew up.

277
00:30:34,438 --> 00:30:37,233
Her father taught English in the village.

278
00:30:48,494 --> 00:30:50,454
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

279
00:31:06,428 --> 00:31:09,223
(BOTH SPEAKING OTHER LANGUAGE)

280
00:31:21,443 --> 00:31:23,320
Well, I'm not going to drink
some foaming cup of

281
00:31:23,487 --> 00:31:25,531
you-know-what-it-is-and-won't-tell-me.

282
00:31:26,490 --> 00:31:27,491
(SPEAKING OTHER LANGUAGE)

283
00:31:29,827 --> 00:31:31,120
(ALL LAUGHING)

284
00:31:31,495 --> 00:31:33,622
GEORGE: That's funny
to everybody, huh? Mmm-hmm.

285
00:31:34,999 --> 00:31:36,792
- (COUGHING)
- (ALL LAUGHING)

286
00:31:37,668 --> 00:31:38,669
Whoo!

287
00:31:46,927 --> 00:31:48,804
(PEOPLE SINGING IN OTHER LANGUAGE)

288
00:31:55,561 --> 00:31:57,563
They're singing the legend of Tarzan.

289
00:31:59,565 --> 00:32:02,401
For many moons,
he was thought to be an evil spirit.

290
00:32:03,527 --> 00:32:05,237
A ghost in the trees.

291
00:32:10,993 --> 00:32:12,202
(ROARING)

292
00:32:15,706 --> 00:32:18,375
They speak of his power
over the animals of the jungle.

293
00:32:20,461 --> 00:32:22,671
Because his spirit came from them.

294
00:32:32,931 --> 00:32:34,099
He understood them

295
00:32:37,061 --> 00:32:38,395
and learned to conquer them.

296
00:32:44,652 --> 00:32:48,405
His ape mother, Kala,
loved him as her own,

297
00:32:48,572 --> 00:32:52,242
and his ape brother, Akut,
treated him with kindness and respect.

298
00:32:56,914 --> 00:32:57,915
(EXHALES SHARPLY)

299
00:32:59,583 --> 00:33:02,127
He considered all men to be his enemies,

300
00:33:02,753 --> 00:33:05,923
since other tribes would hunt his troop
as a rite of passage.

301
00:33:08,092 --> 00:33:09,218
(EXHALES SHARPLY)

302
00:33:17,726 --> 00:33:20,396
JANE: Chief Muviro knew what he was.

303
00:33:20,562 --> 00:33:21,563
He was good to him,

304
00:33:22,648 --> 00:33:24,983
since no man ever started with less.

305
00:33:25,359 --> 00:33:26,944
(SINGING CONTINUES)

306
00:33:36,620 --> 00:33:38,455
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

307
00:33:51,969 --> 00:33:52,970
John?

308
00:33:59,101 --> 00:34:00,769
(JOHN MIMICKING BIRD CALLING)

309
00:34:04,857 --> 00:34:07,401
Blue-bottom rufous towhee.

310
00:34:08,819 --> 00:34:10,738
Mating call.

311
00:34:12,990 --> 00:34:15,075
Be still, my beating heart.

312
00:34:24,960 --> 00:34:26,295
(JOHN MIMICKING BIRD CALLING)

313
00:34:27,004 --> 00:34:28,672
Mandrill.

314
00:34:29,882 --> 00:34:32,134
Also a mating call.

315
00:34:36,972 --> 00:34:38,265
(JOHN GROWLING)

316
00:34:41,143 --> 00:34:42,519
Cheetah.

317
00:34:43,645 --> 00:34:45,022
Mating call.

318
00:34:45,856 --> 00:34:48,984
JANE: Ten, nine,

319
00:34:49,151 --> 00:34:52,029
eight, seven,

320
00:34:53,030 --> 00:34:57,409
six, five, four,

321
00:34:58,702 --> 00:34:59,870
three,

322
00:35:03,624 --> 00:35:04,666
two...

323
00:35:14,885 --> 00:35:17,554
I know you took my handkerchief.

324
00:35:19,014 --> 00:35:21,391
We're from America,
and my father is a professor.

325
00:35:21,558 --> 00:35:24,394
So, I didn't grow up believing in spirits.

326
00:35:33,070 --> 00:35:34,071
Hello.

327
00:35:36,240 --> 00:35:37,741
You're welcome to have it.

328
00:35:40,577 --> 00:35:42,329
Will you speak to me?

329
00:35:57,344 --> 00:35:58,345
Um...

330
00:36:03,976 --> 00:36:04,977
(CHUCKLES)

331
00:36:10,858 --> 00:36:14,528
You must know that this is very peculiar.

332
00:36:14,611 --> 00:36:16,029
(SNIFFS)

333
00:36:16,113 --> 00:36:20,284
I'm not sure my father would
find this very appropriate.

334
00:36:20,367 --> 00:36:22,035
(CONTINUES SNIFFING)

335
00:36:22,119 --> 00:36:23,871
But, um... (CLEARS THROAT)

336
00:36:24,037 --> 00:36:27,291
We must make an effort
to embrace customs...

337
00:36:29,751 --> 00:36:32,170
Oh! I don't think so, wild man!

338
00:36:32,421 --> 00:36:33,714
(EXHALES)

339
00:36:34,423 --> 00:36:35,591
No, no, no. Wait!

340
00:37:19,217 --> 00:37:20,844
(FAINT CRY IN THE DISTANCE)

341
00:37:34,149 --> 00:37:36,193
(PANICKED CHATTER IN OTHER LANGUAGE)

342
00:37:43,533 --> 00:37:45,035
(WOMEN SOBBING)

343
00:37:56,755 --> 00:37:58,215
(SPEAKING OTHER LANGUAGE)

344
00:38:01,885 --> 00:38:04,137
I speak many languages.

345
00:38:05,973 --> 00:38:07,224
(GUN COCKS)

346
00:38:07,307 --> 00:38:08,350
Kneel!

347
00:38:10,185 --> 00:38:13,063
Kuba chief never kneels.

348
00:38:13,271 --> 00:38:14,773
(OFFICERS SHOUTING)

349
00:38:16,274 --> 00:38:18,694
- OFFICER: Down! All of you!
- Get down!

350
00:38:19,361 --> 00:38:20,404
Take aim!

351
00:38:22,239 --> 00:38:23,240
(GROANS)

352
00:38:26,410 --> 00:38:27,995
(OFFICERS CONTINUE SHOUTING)

353
00:38:30,247 --> 00:38:31,748
Come on!

354
00:38:32,332 --> 00:38:33,333
(GUN COCKS)

355
00:38:33,458 --> 00:38:34,459
(GRUNTING)

356
00:38:40,257 --> 00:38:41,258
(CHOKING)

357
00:38:44,678 --> 00:38:45,679
(ALL GRUNTING)

358
00:38:53,437 --> 00:38:54,896
OFFICER: Hold him still!

359
00:39:00,444 --> 00:39:02,362
Tighter! Tighter!

360
00:39:02,446 --> 00:39:03,447
(GRUNTING)

361
00:39:05,198 --> 00:39:08,201
You ain't so tough,
you grotty little monkey boy.

362
00:39:15,792 --> 00:39:17,127
- (GRUNTING)
- (ROPES TIGHTENING)

363
00:39:23,133 --> 00:39:24,843
Some legend, Mr. Rom.

364
00:39:25,010 --> 00:39:27,554
Chief Mbonga will be disappointed.

365
00:39:32,059 --> 00:39:33,643
Round up 10 of the strongest.

366
00:39:34,352 --> 00:39:36,646
- We'll need porters.
- Yes, sir.

367
00:39:37,022 --> 00:39:38,231
This guy right here, sir.

368
00:39:38,315 --> 00:39:39,566
(KUBA PEOPLE PROTESTING)

369
00:39:39,649 --> 00:39:41,651
Grab him, men. You're coming with me!

370
00:39:53,413 --> 00:39:54,456
JANE: Let go of me!

371
00:39:54,998 --> 00:39:56,416
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

372
00:39:58,919 --> 00:40:00,003
John!

373
00:40:00,629 --> 00:40:02,339
- (INDISTINCT CHATTER)
- (JANE GRUNTING)

374
00:40:06,343 --> 00:40:07,636
Get off! John!

375
00:40:07,803 --> 00:40:10,722
Must have been something
the first moment you saw her.

376
00:40:12,224 --> 00:40:14,768
After all the negresses and baboons.

377
00:40:15,143 --> 00:40:16,144
(MIMICKING BABOONS)

378
00:40:16,478 --> 00:40:17,854
(MAJOR KERCKHOVER LAUGHING)

379
00:40:19,689 --> 00:40:20,982
JANE: John!

380
00:40:23,318 --> 00:40:24,653
- (GUN FIRES)
- (GROANS)

381
00:40:30,659 --> 00:40:31,660
(GROANS)

382
00:40:38,166 --> 00:40:39,167
(GUNS COCKING)

383
00:40:44,464 --> 00:40:45,715
(PANICKED CHATTER)

384
00:41:04,818 --> 00:41:05,819
(GRUNTING)

385
00:41:11,074 --> 00:41:13,076
MAJOR KERCKHOVER:
Mr. Rom, we'll bring him down.

386
00:41:13,243 --> 00:41:14,870
Go! Go!

387
00:41:15,495 --> 00:41:16,496
(GRUNTS)

388
00:41:21,293 --> 00:41:22,335
Get the Maxims loaded!

389
00:41:22,919 --> 00:41:23,920
Hurry!

390
00:41:26,798 --> 00:41:27,799
(GROANS)

391
00:41:31,428 --> 00:41:34,639
Focus fire on the boilers.
Below the chimney.

392
00:41:38,435 --> 00:41:39,811
Pull away!

393
00:41:43,398 --> 00:41:44,566
Where do you think you're going?

394
00:41:49,321 --> 00:41:50,697
(JANE BREATHING HEAVILY)

395
00:41:55,744 --> 00:41:57,662
I need you to scream for me.

396
00:42:00,123 --> 00:42:01,708
Like a damsel?

397
00:42:02,375 --> 00:42:03,376
(SPITS)

398
00:42:13,553 --> 00:42:15,180
No matter.

399
00:42:16,139 --> 00:42:18,141
He's Tarzan, you're Jane.

400
00:42:20,769 --> 00:42:22,270
He'll come for you.

401
00:42:25,357 --> 00:42:26,358
(GRUNTS)

402
00:42:37,827 --> 00:42:40,163
John! John!

403
00:42:44,125 --> 00:42:46,086
John! John...

404
00:42:47,796 --> 00:42:48,797
(GASPING)

405
00:43:04,020 --> 00:43:05,855
(WOMEN SOBBING)

406
00:43:11,361 --> 00:43:12,821
They came for me, Kwete.

407
00:43:12,988 --> 00:43:14,406
KWETE: This was not done by you.

408
00:43:16,491 --> 00:43:17,867
Do you know who they were?

409
00:43:18,618 --> 00:43:21,288
We've heard of whites
that come and fight for money,

410
00:43:21,454 --> 00:43:23,039
do not wear Belgian colors...

411
00:43:23,206 --> 00:43:24,541
Called Force Publique.

412
00:43:25,667 --> 00:43:28,169
The man I interviewed in Belgium
told me about them.

413
00:43:28,336 --> 00:43:29,879
Did anyone mention a man named Rom?

414
00:43:31,131 --> 00:43:32,674
Nobody gave up any names.

415
00:43:32,841 --> 00:43:36,928
But Leon Rom
is King Leopold's envoy to the Congo.

416
00:43:38,513 --> 00:43:39,639
Any other revelations?

417
00:43:40,682 --> 00:43:42,225
Not from me.

418
00:43:43,184 --> 00:43:44,519
Why do you say they came to get you?

419
00:43:49,899 --> 00:43:50,900
(GRUNTS)

420
00:43:52,235 --> 00:43:56,239
JOHN: The boat is traveling upstream,
which will slow it down.

421
00:43:56,406 --> 00:43:58,491
We should get to Mbonga's mountain
before them

422
00:43:58,658 --> 00:44:01,578
if we take this route
through the Mangani lands.

423
00:44:01,745 --> 00:44:02,829
How do you know where they're going?

424
00:44:02,996 --> 00:44:05,123
- KWETE: This route--
- JOHN: It's longer.

425
00:44:05,290 --> 00:44:07,042
But it is where
they are building the railroad.

426
00:44:07,208 --> 00:44:08,877
We can ride it part of the way.

427
00:44:10,253 --> 00:44:11,254
Good.

428
00:44:13,298 --> 00:44:14,549
GEORGE: John?

429
00:44:15,425 --> 00:44:16,760
John?

430
00:44:18,011 --> 00:44:19,512
John!

431
00:44:20,388 --> 00:44:22,599
Fine! I'm still coming with you.

432
00:44:23,433 --> 00:44:24,851
You can't keep up.

433
00:44:25,018 --> 00:44:26,936
I might not be able
to keep up with Tarzan,

434
00:44:27,103 --> 00:44:28,730
but I sure as hell can keep up with you.

435
00:44:28,897 --> 00:44:30,106
It is not wise.

436
00:44:30,273 --> 00:44:31,858
Falling behind means certain death.

437
00:44:32,025 --> 00:44:33,902
I spent over half my life in the wilds.

438
00:44:34,069 --> 00:44:36,279
Besides, nobody here
is better than me with a rifle.

439
00:44:36,446 --> 00:44:37,614
That one right there,

440
00:44:37,781 --> 00:44:39,741
he'd still be choked out
redder than a cardinal's ass

441
00:44:39,908 --> 00:44:41,451
if it weren't for me. And that's--

442
00:44:41,785 --> 00:44:42,827
(YELPS)

443
00:44:42,911 --> 00:44:44,329
You think I care about my life?

444
00:44:44,496 --> 00:44:45,789
Get your mitts off me!

445
00:44:46,373 --> 00:44:48,708
- If you had just--
- If I'd just what?

446
00:44:48,875 --> 00:44:50,502
Left you in England in your castle?

447
00:44:51,836 --> 00:44:55,840
They have my wife and their families.

448
00:45:47,851 --> 00:45:52,355
Whoever you are,
we're here by royal invitation.

449
00:45:52,522 --> 00:45:54,691
As guests of King Leopold.

450
00:45:55,775 --> 00:45:59,195
Lady Clayton,
I orchestrated the invitation.

451
00:46:00,488 --> 00:46:02,240
And you were not included.

452
00:46:03,199 --> 00:46:05,201
Nor was Dr. Williams.

453
00:46:07,912 --> 00:46:12,375
A tribe of savages
is trying to tear your husband apart

454
00:46:12,542 --> 00:46:14,419
and maybe butcher him and eat him.

455
00:46:15,086 --> 00:46:17,130
And I'm going to deliver him to them.

456
00:46:17,297 --> 00:46:18,715
And once they've dispatched with him,

457
00:46:18,882 --> 00:46:21,217
(LAUGHING) Dr. Williams
will not be left as a witness,

458
00:46:21,384 --> 00:46:22,635
that's clear.

459
00:46:25,013 --> 00:46:26,848
Which begs the question,

460
00:46:27,932 --> 00:46:29,809
where does that leave you?

461
00:46:36,816 --> 00:46:39,819
You'll notice
none of the natives are smiling.

462
00:46:47,160 --> 00:46:49,078
That one's your friend?

463
00:46:51,247 --> 00:46:52,248
They all are.

464
00:47:00,673 --> 00:47:02,926
You do know
that the right side of your mustache

465
00:47:03,092 --> 00:47:05,470
is just a little lower than the left?

466
00:47:30,662 --> 00:47:31,663
(PANTING)

467
00:47:43,132 --> 00:47:44,717
(GEORGE WHEEZING)

468
00:47:46,761 --> 00:47:47,762
(GROWLS)

469
00:47:48,513 --> 00:47:49,847
GEORGE: John!

470
00:47:50,014 --> 00:47:51,599
John!

471
00:48:05,196 --> 00:48:06,906
(GEORGE PANTING)

472
00:48:09,075 --> 00:48:10,076
(COUGHING)

473
00:48:15,123 --> 00:48:16,124
Different kind of wilds.

474
00:48:23,506 --> 00:48:24,757
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWS IN THE DISTANCE)

475
00:48:26,175 --> 00:48:28,678
How are we supposed to catch
a train going 40 miles an hour?

476
00:48:33,182 --> 00:48:34,684
Gravity.

477
00:48:50,450 --> 00:48:51,534
Shit!

478
00:48:53,328 --> 00:48:54,329
(GEORGE SCREAMING)

479
00:48:54,579 --> 00:48:56,289
(GEORGE GROANING)

480
00:49:01,878 --> 00:49:02,879
(PANTING)

481
00:49:23,775 --> 00:49:24,984
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING)

482
00:49:31,699 --> 00:49:32,700
(PANTING)

483
00:49:58,685 --> 00:50:00,144
Climb on my back.

484
00:50:04,148 --> 00:50:05,149
(GEORGE GRUNTS)

485
00:50:05,316 --> 00:50:06,609
Right. Legs, too.

486
00:50:08,111 --> 00:50:09,112
(GRUNTING)

487
00:50:12,365 --> 00:50:15,159
Don't think for a second
you're saving my life.

488
00:50:17,245 --> 00:50:18,705
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING)

489
00:50:21,999 --> 00:50:23,042
(GEORGE SCREAMING)

490
00:50:40,143 --> 00:50:41,144
(THUDDING)

491
00:51:26,856 --> 00:51:28,191
(ALL GRUNTING)

492
00:51:40,828 --> 00:51:41,829
(GRUNTS)

493
00:51:46,876 --> 00:51:49,086
Give me the keys to the chains.

494
00:51:49,295 --> 00:51:50,296
(GLASS SHATTERING)

495
00:51:57,887 --> 00:51:58,888
(BOTH GRUNTING)

496
00:52:04,268 --> 00:52:05,269
JOHN: Are you the commander?

497
00:52:05,436 --> 00:52:06,479
Don't tell him anything.

498
00:52:07,688 --> 00:52:08,689
(GUN COCKING)

499
00:52:08,773 --> 00:52:11,692
Those are some mighty big earlobes
you got there, son.

500
00:52:14,237 --> 00:52:15,238
(GUN FIRES)

501
00:52:17,907 --> 00:52:20,243
Do you think that was a lucky shot?

502
00:52:21,202 --> 00:52:24,831
(BOTH SPEAKING FRENCH)

503
00:52:27,083 --> 00:52:28,543
I'm just an engineer for the bridge.

504
00:52:29,836 --> 00:52:32,672
And how many men
have been enslaved to build your bridge?

505
00:52:33,923 --> 00:52:35,466
Eight hundred.

506
00:52:35,633 --> 00:52:38,010
Plus, this group of natives.

507
00:52:38,177 --> 00:52:41,347
Please, I'm here to build bridges
for Monsieur Rom's new army.

508
00:52:41,514 --> 00:52:42,682
I have no part in that.

509
00:52:43,850 --> 00:52:44,934
What army?

510
00:52:50,940 --> 00:52:51,983
ENGINEER: The railroads,

511
00:52:52,149 --> 00:52:54,151
combined with the navigable rivers

512
00:52:55,278 --> 00:52:59,782
put 60% of Congo
within three days of a fort.

513
00:53:01,951 --> 00:53:04,620
The forts are done,
but the army has not come.

514
00:53:04,787 --> 00:53:06,038
Where are they?

515
00:53:06,205 --> 00:53:07,290
I don't know.

516
00:53:07,957 --> 00:53:09,584
They were supposed to be here months ago.

517
00:53:10,251 --> 00:53:12,587
But they said
the King is yet to pay for them.

518
00:53:12,753 --> 00:53:14,171
How many are there?

519
00:53:16,591 --> 00:53:17,800
Twenty thousand.

520
00:53:19,302 --> 00:53:21,345
And they are not regular soldiers.

521
00:53:22,471 --> 00:53:24,307
They are mercenaries.

522
00:53:24,807 --> 00:53:26,893
Known to enjoy killing for a living.

523
00:53:27,059 --> 00:53:29,020
Twenty thousand men, 50 forts.

524
00:53:29,186 --> 00:53:33,649
That's 400 bloodthirsty bastards
armed with a Maxim gun

525
00:53:33,816 --> 00:53:35,818
and repeating rifles at each one.

526
00:53:35,985 --> 00:53:39,822
He'll end up enslaving the entire country
to get what he wants.

527
00:53:40,489 --> 00:53:42,199
People won't stand a chance.

528
00:53:43,701 --> 00:53:45,536
What is Mr. Rom's part in this?

529
00:53:45,703 --> 00:53:48,956
It's his plan.
He is in charge of all of it.

530
00:53:51,626 --> 00:53:54,837
They expect
he will be named Governor General soon.

531
00:54:02,762 --> 00:54:04,180
JANE: No, no, no. Wait!

532
00:54:10,353 --> 00:54:11,896
Wait! Please!

533
00:54:21,864 --> 00:54:22,865
(ROARING)

534
00:54:23,199 --> 00:54:24,200
(GASPS)

535
00:54:27,870 --> 00:54:28,871
(ROARING)

536
00:54:38,172 --> 00:54:40,257
(GROANING)

537
00:54:56,732 --> 00:54:57,733
(WAILING)

538
00:55:23,759 --> 00:55:25,219
(WAILING)

539
00:55:31,851 --> 00:55:32,935
(CONTINUES WAILING)

540
00:55:55,249 --> 00:55:56,250
(GUNS COCKING)

541
00:56:00,379 --> 00:56:01,547
(SPEAKING OTHER LANGUAGE)

542
00:56:01,756 --> 00:56:03,340
Shut it, clucker!

543
00:56:10,097 --> 00:56:11,098
(MEN LAUGHING)

544
00:56:11,182 --> 00:56:15,770
Now, if you do
anything unladylike in there,

545
00:56:17,229 --> 00:56:18,814
he drowns.

546
00:56:38,167 --> 00:56:39,794
JANE: Enjoying your peep show?

547
00:56:43,172 --> 00:56:46,550
Of course I know
you can see me, Lady Clayton.

548
00:57:00,022 --> 00:57:02,233
Are you a religious man, Mr. Rom?

549
00:57:02,399 --> 00:57:04,860
Oh. No. Madagascar spider silk.

550
00:57:08,197 --> 00:57:10,699
My priest purchased it for me
in Jerusalem

551
00:57:10,866 --> 00:57:12,493
when I was nine.

552
00:57:13,369 --> 00:57:16,205
Sounds like you and your priest
were awfully close.

553
00:57:16,914 --> 00:57:17,957
Why?

554
00:57:25,714 --> 00:57:26,966
I want you to know,

555
00:57:27,133 --> 00:57:30,511
I think your husband
had no right to bring you along.

556
00:57:30,678 --> 00:57:31,887
I brought myself, Mr. Rom.

557
00:57:32,054 --> 00:57:33,264
Of course.

558
00:57:33,430 --> 00:57:35,891
But he was supposed to be
the only casualty.

559
00:57:36,058 --> 00:57:39,854
Aside from the entire country of people
you're enslaving, of course.

560
00:57:41,355 --> 00:57:42,356
Would you pass the pepper?

561
00:57:49,238 --> 00:57:50,239
(GROANING)

562
00:58:15,973 --> 00:58:18,225
It can also serve as a necklace.

563
00:58:18,309 --> 00:58:19,435
(JANE SCOFFS)

564
00:58:30,738 --> 00:58:35,784
On my last visit to Europe,
I attended a few lectures at the Sorbonne.

565
00:58:36,452 --> 00:58:39,413
The King of France got a soft clap.

566
00:58:39,580 --> 00:58:41,749
Henry Morton Stanley,
a bastard orphan by birth,

567
00:58:41,916 --> 00:58:43,500
got a standing ovation.

568
00:58:44,668 --> 00:58:45,669
(CHUCKLES)

569
00:58:47,129 --> 00:58:49,006
People love a good story.

570
00:58:50,758 --> 00:58:54,345
Yeah, a few are born blue bloods,
like your husband.

571
00:58:57,973 --> 00:59:00,476
But everyone can relate
to a low-born scrapper

572
00:59:00,643 --> 00:59:04,313
who rescued his king from bankruptcy
and saved the honor of his nation.

573
00:59:04,480 --> 00:59:06,857
That is a man who will never be forgotten.

574
00:59:11,570 --> 00:59:14,156
My king's army is due in six days.

575
00:59:14,573 --> 00:59:17,826
All I've left to do
is deliver Tarzan to Chief Mbonga.

576
00:59:20,537 --> 00:59:23,958
(CHUCKLES) Yeah,
I'd hoped you'd recognize the name.

577
00:59:26,335 --> 00:59:29,505
I'm aware of his obsessive desire
to kill your husband,

578
00:59:29,672 --> 00:59:31,590
but I've yet to discover the cause.

579
00:59:31,757 --> 00:59:34,009
What did Tarzan do?

580
00:59:35,970 --> 00:59:38,013
He killed his only son.

581
00:59:41,225 --> 00:59:42,768
- Oh.
- Hmm.

582
00:59:45,896 --> 00:59:51,193
And get ready, because that is nothing
compared to what he will do to you.

583
00:59:52,528 --> 00:59:54,029
(INHALES DEEPLY)

584
00:59:55,239 --> 01:00:00,202
Your husband's wildness disturbs me
more than I can easily express.

585
01:00:01,704 --> 01:00:04,248
Whereas your spirit...

586
01:00:17,094 --> 01:00:19,596
My knife, please.

587
01:00:21,056 --> 01:00:22,599
Slowly.

588
01:00:22,766 --> 01:00:24,768
Your friend won't float.

589
01:00:35,070 --> 01:00:36,572
Thank you.

590
01:00:40,576 --> 01:00:41,577
(RINGS BELL)

591
01:00:42,578 --> 01:00:43,579
(DOOR OPENS)

592
01:00:46,999 --> 01:00:49,084
Lady Clayton's finished.

593
01:00:49,293 --> 01:00:50,294
(SCOFFS)

594
01:00:51,253 --> 01:00:55,215
A normal man can do the impossible
to save the woman he loves.

595
01:00:56,258 --> 01:00:59,053
My husband is no normal man.

596
01:01:03,599 --> 01:01:04,600
(DOOR CLOSES)

597
01:01:15,819 --> 01:01:17,279
(BRAKES SCREECHING)

598
01:01:28,791 --> 01:01:30,501
KWETE: You cannot go alone.

599
01:01:30,667 --> 01:01:32,878
They'd consider seven a raid.

600
01:01:33,629 --> 01:01:35,297
None of us would survive.

601
01:01:37,800 --> 01:01:40,886
This says it's against the law
to pay natives to work.

602
01:01:41,053 --> 01:01:44,556
And this is the ledger
of all the slaves taken so far.

603
01:01:44,723 --> 01:01:47,059
Slave labor, diamonds everywhere.

604
01:01:47,226 --> 01:01:51,105
Rom's going to make his monarch
the richest king in the world.

605
01:01:51,271 --> 01:01:52,689
Dr. Williams, you have your evidence.

606
01:01:54,483 --> 01:01:56,568
I'll take care of Rom.

607
01:01:57,778 --> 01:02:00,280
(SPEAKING OTHER LANGUAGE)

608
01:02:01,573 --> 01:02:03,826
Well, I have no choice.

609
01:02:03,992 --> 01:02:05,577
We'd lose two days going around.

610
01:02:05,744 --> 01:02:08,163
- Going around what?
- Mangani.

611
01:02:08,330 --> 01:02:10,833
Those gorillas you used to live with?

612
01:02:10,999 --> 01:02:12,167
They're not gorillas.

613
01:02:12,334 --> 01:02:14,920
Gorillas are gentle. Mangani are not.

614
01:02:23,011 --> 01:02:25,848
I never left a friend in trouble,
or a partner in the lurch.

615
01:02:26,014 --> 01:02:28,225
I'm not about to start now.

616
01:02:28,392 --> 01:02:30,811
Stop calling me "doctor."
My name's George.

617
01:02:31,437 --> 01:02:34,523
We'll keep your proof safe, George.

618
01:02:34,690 --> 01:02:35,691
I know.

619
01:02:36,817 --> 01:02:38,402
Meet us in Boma.

620
01:02:39,111 --> 01:02:40,112
If we don't make it back...

621
01:02:40,279 --> 01:02:42,656
We will. With your families.

622
01:02:42,823 --> 01:02:44,408
...get the books
to my grandfather in London.

623
01:02:46,034 --> 01:02:47,077
Still not waiting for you.

624
01:02:47,244 --> 01:02:48,495
Tell me something I didn't know.

625
01:02:48,704 --> 01:02:49,872
(ALL CHEERING)

626
01:03:01,300 --> 01:03:03,719
What I wouldn't give
for a horse right now.

627
01:03:05,220 --> 01:03:07,181
Why is it people don't ride zebras?

628
01:03:07,806 --> 01:03:09,892
Well, horses kick to escape.

629
01:03:10,058 --> 01:03:12,019
Zebras continue until you're dead.

630
01:03:12,936 --> 01:03:14,480
"Zee-bra," "zeb-ra."
"Tom-ay-to," "to-mah-to."

631
01:03:14,646 --> 01:03:17,399
It's nearly impossible to take the wild
out of something born to it.

632
01:03:17,566 --> 01:03:19,151
It seemed to have worked with you.

633
01:03:20,736 --> 01:03:23,655
Look, I feel foolish for asking,

634
01:03:24,323 --> 01:03:26,783
but can you really talk to the animals?

635
01:03:26,950 --> 01:03:30,412
You're an educated man, Dr. Williams.
You tell me.

636
01:03:32,331 --> 01:03:33,540
(OSTRICHES TRILLING)

637
01:03:39,421 --> 01:03:40,589
(SQUAWKING)

638
01:03:41,757 --> 01:03:43,467
(LAUGHING NERVOUSLY)
Hey! Hey, pretty lady!

639
01:03:46,345 --> 01:03:48,347
That's a male.

640
01:03:48,514 --> 01:03:50,265
He's warning us to stay clear.

641
01:03:51,433 --> 01:03:55,103
You're trying to tell me
those things are deadly?

642
01:03:55,270 --> 01:03:57,022
If you get too close,
he'll knock you to the ground

643
01:03:57,189 --> 01:03:59,483
and disembowel you
with those three-inch talons.

644
01:04:01,068 --> 01:04:02,653
No ostrich is going to kill me.

645
01:04:03,737 --> 01:04:05,364
Well, then try and ride him.

646
01:04:05,656 --> 01:04:08,200
(SCOFFS) You'd like that, wouldn't you?

647
01:04:08,951 --> 01:04:09,952
(SQUAWKS)

648
01:04:13,539 --> 01:04:14,540
Oh...

649
01:04:14,957 --> 01:04:16,792
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

650
01:04:25,133 --> 01:04:28,845
GEORGE: Damn!
That is one odious aroma. Whew, God!

651
01:04:29,012 --> 01:04:30,806
JOHN: Keep your voice low.

652
01:04:31,682 --> 01:04:33,392
(MANGANI GRUNTING)

653
01:04:35,185 --> 01:04:36,603
Is that them?

654
01:04:40,607 --> 01:04:42,359
(GROWLS)

655
01:04:42,943 --> 01:04:44,403
You don't want to do that, George.

656
01:04:44,987 --> 01:04:47,823
Kill one, and the rest won't stop
until they have torn you to pieces.

657
01:04:50,242 --> 01:04:51,785
So how do you want to play this, then?

658
01:04:52,369 --> 01:04:55,664
Their leader will come down,
and we'll fight.

659
01:04:57,499 --> 01:04:59,209
You're going to fight one of those?

660
01:04:59,376 --> 01:05:02,504
I wish. I have to fight Akut.

661
01:05:04,214 --> 01:05:06,133
He was my brother once.

662
01:05:06,800 --> 01:05:08,302
And now he'll consider me a deserter.

663
01:05:08,927 --> 01:05:12,306
Whatever happens, do not interfere.

664
01:05:13,181 --> 01:05:14,516
Understand?

665
01:05:14,600 --> 01:05:15,601
Mmm-hmm.

666
01:05:21,315 --> 01:05:22,524
GEORGE: Christ Almighty.

667
01:05:25,611 --> 01:05:27,029
That's Akut?

668
01:05:28,030 --> 01:05:30,240
You sure you don't want me to shoot him?

669
01:05:34,036 --> 01:05:35,495
Promise me.

670
01:05:38,874 --> 01:05:40,626
(EXHALING SHARPLY)

671
01:05:43,712 --> 01:05:45,547
(GROWLING)

672
01:05:47,758 --> 01:05:48,759
(GRUNTS)

673
01:05:59,561 --> 01:06:00,562
(ROARING)

674
01:06:13,575 --> 01:06:14,701
(GROANING)

675
01:06:20,791 --> 01:06:21,917
(GROANING LOUDLY)

676
01:06:33,428 --> 01:06:34,846
(GRUNTING)

677
01:06:49,945 --> 01:06:51,822
(GROANING)

678
01:06:59,955 --> 01:07:01,915
Get on your knees and bow.

679
01:07:02,457 --> 01:07:04,292
Right now!

680
01:07:04,960 --> 01:07:06,962
Expose your most vulnerable parts!

681
01:07:16,388 --> 01:07:17,389
(ROARING)

682
01:07:22,144 --> 01:07:24,312
(PANTING) You want me
to lick his nuts, too?

683
01:07:24,479 --> 01:07:25,981
If you want to live.

684
01:07:27,607 --> 01:07:28,817
George...

685
01:07:28,984 --> 01:07:30,152
I wasn't going to!

686
01:07:31,153 --> 01:07:32,487
Well, it looked like you were.

687
01:07:32,821 --> 01:07:33,822
(GRUNTING)

688
01:07:40,871 --> 01:07:42,873
(GROANING)

689
01:07:48,044 --> 01:07:49,045
(PANTING)

690
01:07:52,174 --> 01:07:53,508
GEORGE: Is he coming back?

691
01:07:53,759 --> 01:07:57,137
No. It was quite decisive.

692
01:07:57,304 --> 01:07:59,765
If this bite gets infected,
you're going to have problems.

693
01:08:00,348 --> 01:08:01,349
Then there is this.

694
01:08:06,062 --> 01:08:08,440
Now, you know
I was not going to lick his--

695
01:08:08,607 --> 01:08:09,608
It looked like you were.

696
01:08:09,691 --> 01:08:10,942
- Well, I wasn't.
- (GROANS LOUDLY)

697
01:08:15,280 --> 01:08:18,867
You aren't going anywhere
until we get this stitched up.

698
01:08:24,748 --> 01:08:26,541
Are you eating them?

699
01:08:27,042 --> 01:08:29,419
- Tastes like bacon.
- Ew.

700
01:08:29,503 --> 01:08:31,713
You get us a nice, fat snake,
I'd grub on that.

701
01:08:31,880 --> 01:08:35,175
Snake's good meat.
I ain't eating no damn ant.

702
01:08:35,342 --> 01:08:37,093
Well, suit yourself.

703
01:08:38,261 --> 01:08:39,638
And when you're finished,

704
01:08:39,805 --> 01:08:43,099
chew the flowers into a poultice
and wipe it on the cut with a rubber.

705
01:08:44,392 --> 01:08:45,852
It'll hold.

706
01:08:48,855 --> 01:08:49,898
Are you aware that you always say

707
01:08:50,065 --> 01:08:52,025
you're not going to do something
right before you do it?

708
01:08:52,192 --> 01:08:54,152
Yeah? Well...

709
01:08:54,319 --> 01:08:56,196
That's only since
I've been saddled with your company.

710
01:08:59,783 --> 01:09:01,076
How is it?

711
01:09:01,243 --> 01:09:02,869
It's manageable.

712
01:09:03,495 --> 01:09:04,788
Pain...

713
01:09:06,998 --> 01:09:09,125
I got too much experience with it.

714
01:09:15,715 --> 01:09:16,800
(SIGHS)

715
01:09:16,883 --> 01:09:19,261
The Civil War was dark fighting.

716
01:09:20,887 --> 01:09:22,764
But I was proud to be part of it.

717
01:09:25,141 --> 01:09:26,935
Changed me, though.

718
01:09:27,978 --> 01:09:31,648
Afterward, I was
a walking, talking powder keg.

719
01:09:34,442 --> 01:09:37,612
Joined up to fight
Maximilian down in Mexico.

720
01:09:39,489 --> 01:09:43,076
Then worked as an Indian fighter.

721
01:09:44,411 --> 01:09:46,580
Did both those for the money.

722
01:09:48,957 --> 01:09:50,709
I was young.

723
01:09:51,543 --> 01:09:53,420
But that's no excuse.

724
01:09:55,547 --> 01:09:56,548
(SIGHS)

725
01:09:58,592 --> 01:10:00,176
Mexico was bad.

726
01:10:02,304 --> 01:10:04,514
But what we did to the Indians...

727
01:10:04,598 --> 01:10:05,599
(SCOFFS)

728
01:10:14,482 --> 01:10:16,484
I'm no better than those Belgians.

729
01:10:19,529 --> 01:10:21,239
(ELEPHANTS TRUMPETING)

730
01:10:46,014 --> 01:10:47,515
My old friend.

731
01:11:04,032 --> 01:11:07,827
The Teke say an elephant's eyes
speak the greatest language.

732
01:11:10,622 --> 01:11:13,416
What else can make you feel so much
without a word?

733
01:11:14,042 --> 01:11:15,335
(BABY ELEPHANT TRUMPETING)

734
01:12:14,436 --> 01:12:15,520
(HIPPOS SNORTING AND GRUNTING)

735
01:12:33,788 --> 01:12:36,916
Is Mr. Rom ready
for some more scintillating conversation?

736
01:12:38,126 --> 01:12:41,880
He was the only reason
you weren't serviced.

737
01:12:42,047 --> 01:12:43,673
JANE: Serviced?

738
01:12:43,840 --> 01:12:45,800
Is that what your mother would call it?

739
01:12:49,679 --> 01:12:52,432
(SPEAKING OTHER LANGUAGE)

740
01:12:52,599 --> 01:12:53,641
Shut your mouth!

741
01:13:00,398 --> 01:13:01,816
(INHALES DEEPLY)

742
01:13:03,985 --> 01:13:04,986
(GRUNTING)

743
01:13:07,489 --> 01:13:10,658
MAJOR KERCKHOVER:
Stop the boat! Stop the boat!

744
01:13:10,909 --> 01:13:12,285
Turn it around!

745
01:13:14,037 --> 01:13:15,205
(BOAT WHISTLE BLOWING)

746
01:13:18,166 --> 01:13:19,375
(PULLING UP CAGE)

747
01:13:19,501 --> 01:13:20,668
(GRUNTING)

748
01:13:29,135 --> 01:13:30,136
(GASPING)

749
01:13:34,099 --> 01:13:37,018
Stop shooting! You'll hit the girl!

750
01:13:49,197 --> 01:13:50,573
That woman.

751
01:13:51,658 --> 01:13:53,034
(BOTH PANTING)

752
01:14:06,548 --> 01:14:08,091
(BIRDS SQUAWKING)

753
01:14:21,729 --> 01:14:22,730
Wait!

754
01:14:23,773 --> 01:14:26,609
They'll follow my tracks. Go and get help.

755
01:14:26,901 --> 01:14:27,902
Go!

756
01:14:33,700 --> 01:14:34,701
(GASPS)

757
01:14:36,161 --> 01:14:37,370
(ROARING)

758
01:15:27,128 --> 01:15:28,296
(GROWLING)

759
01:15:49,776 --> 01:15:50,860
(GROWLING)

760
01:15:59,494 --> 01:16:01,454
JANE: Promise you won't hurt them?

761
01:16:17,679 --> 01:16:19,847
- (GUN FIRES)
- No! Stop!

762
01:16:32,860 --> 01:16:34,404
(DISTANT SCREAMING)

763
01:16:37,991 --> 01:16:39,784
JANE: Please, stop!

764
01:16:41,369 --> 01:16:42,203
John!

765
01:16:42,578 --> 01:16:43,579
(PANTING)

766
01:16:50,712 --> 01:16:53,381
JANE: Stop! Stop it! Stop!

767
01:16:55,675 --> 01:16:56,676
(GRUNTING)

768
01:17:00,096 --> 01:17:01,306
Stop it! Please!

769
01:17:04,851 --> 01:17:07,020
Please! Please!

770
01:17:07,186 --> 01:17:08,229
Come on!

771
01:17:08,396 --> 01:17:09,689
MAJOR KERCKHOVER: Move out!

772
01:17:12,358 --> 01:17:13,609
(GROWLING)

773
01:17:26,205 --> 01:17:27,206
(PANTING)

774
01:17:36,758 --> 01:17:37,759
(ROARING)

775
01:17:38,176 --> 01:17:39,177
(GUN COCKING)

776
01:17:39,469 --> 01:17:40,720
(BREATHING SHAKILY)

777
01:17:52,607 --> 01:17:53,608
(GROWLS)

778
01:17:55,735 --> 01:17:56,736
(PANTING)

779
01:18:03,201 --> 01:18:04,202
(WHIMPERING)

780
01:18:16,005 --> 01:18:17,382
(RUSTLING)

781
01:18:25,014 --> 01:18:26,015
(TWIG SNAPS)

782
01:18:26,224 --> 01:18:27,225
(GASPS)

783
01:18:27,308 --> 01:18:28,309
(GROWLING)

784
01:18:28,810 --> 01:18:30,812
- (ROARS)
- (JOHN GRUNTING)

785
01:18:56,671 --> 01:18:58,297
(JOHN ULULATING)

786
01:19:01,467 --> 01:19:03,553
MAJOR KERCKHOVER:
What was that?

787
01:19:04,178 --> 01:19:05,221
ROM: Tarzan.

788
01:19:05,930 --> 01:19:08,099
Although it sounded
different than I thought.

789
01:19:09,434 --> 01:19:10,435
Better.

790
01:19:12,979 --> 01:19:14,564
(GEORGE PANTING)

791
01:19:25,032 --> 01:19:26,159
Schmidt-Rubin.

792
01:19:26,325 --> 01:19:27,326
(GUN COCKING)

793
01:19:32,248 --> 01:19:33,458
John!

794
01:19:35,543 --> 01:19:36,544
John!

795
01:19:37,378 --> 01:19:38,379
Stop!

796
01:20:02,111 --> 01:20:03,446
(KALA SHRIEKING)

797
01:20:06,908 --> 01:20:07,909
(WHIMPERS)

798
01:20:22,632 --> 01:20:24,133
(EXHALING SHARPLY)

799
01:20:37,855 --> 01:20:38,856
(GASPS)

800
01:20:48,157 --> 01:20:49,158
(GRUNTS)

801
01:21:01,629 --> 01:21:02,838
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

802
01:21:54,724 --> 01:21:55,725
(GRUNTING)

803
01:22:02,231 --> 01:22:03,482
JANE: John!

804
01:22:10,990 --> 01:22:13,951
Now, you feel my pain.

805
01:22:16,579 --> 01:22:17,580
(YELLING)

806
01:22:30,134 --> 01:22:31,135
(ALL GRUNTING)

807
01:22:39,727 --> 01:22:41,020
(YELLS)

808
01:22:47,151 --> 01:22:48,944
(PANTING)

809
01:22:50,946 --> 01:22:52,615
(MBONGA CONTINUES YELLING)

810
01:23:16,555 --> 01:23:17,556
(BOTH PANTING)

811
01:23:21,769 --> 01:23:22,770
JOHN: I'm not your enemy.

812
01:23:22,937 --> 01:23:24,897
Rom's buying an army with your jewels.

813
01:23:25,064 --> 01:23:27,608
- They cannot touch us!
- You know nothing!

814
01:23:27,775 --> 01:23:30,778
Your lands are full of diamonds.
He'll come back for them.

815
01:23:31,529 --> 01:23:32,530
(GROANING)

816
01:24:00,307 --> 01:24:01,308
(GRUNTS)

817
01:24:01,475 --> 01:24:03,227
Your chief is under my knife!

818
01:24:03,978 --> 01:24:05,438
You are under my knife!

819
01:24:07,523 --> 01:24:09,150
Finish it.

820
01:24:09,316 --> 01:24:10,693
Finish it!

821
01:24:10,860 --> 01:24:11,986
Stop!

822
01:24:13,320 --> 01:24:15,114
(BOTH PANTING)

823
01:24:19,118 --> 01:24:22,037
Your son killed the only person
who ever cared about me.

824
01:24:22,204 --> 01:24:23,247
It was an animal.

825
01:24:23,414 --> 01:24:26,167
She was my mother.

826
01:24:29,378 --> 01:24:30,921
MBONGA: How was he to know?

827
01:24:32,840 --> 01:24:35,426
My son was just a boy!

828
01:24:36,093 --> 01:24:37,845
Not like you!

829
01:24:40,890 --> 01:24:43,017
Where was your honor?

830
01:24:55,237 --> 01:24:56,906
I had none.

831
01:24:59,158 --> 01:25:00,493
I had none.

832
01:25:02,411 --> 01:25:03,412
(AKUT ROARING)

833
01:25:23,349 --> 01:25:24,850
(MANGANI ROARING)

834
01:25:40,157 --> 01:25:42,701
GEORGE: Can we please just stop this?

835
01:25:42,868 --> 01:25:46,580
We won't get all of you, or you us.

836
01:25:46,747 --> 01:25:47,832
But Rom will.

837
01:25:48,749 --> 01:25:50,751
GEORGE: He'll wipe you out.

838
01:25:50,918 --> 01:25:54,338
Every last one of you.
Like you never even existed.

839
01:25:57,049 --> 01:25:59,176
You think that's impossible?

840
01:25:59,802 --> 01:26:02,346
You're looking at a man
that's seen it happen.

841
01:26:21,156 --> 01:26:22,491
(BREATHING SHAKILY)

842
01:26:30,499 --> 01:26:32,376
(JOHN ULULATING)

843
01:26:43,429 --> 01:26:45,097
(SIGHING IN RELIEF)

844
01:27:17,129 --> 01:27:18,339
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

845
01:27:36,148 --> 01:27:37,399
Rom's got the diamonds.

846
01:27:37,566 --> 01:27:40,361
There's 1,000 men down there
and 20,000 more on the way.

847
01:27:41,236 --> 01:27:42,321
We're screwed.

848
01:27:42,488 --> 01:27:43,530
Where are you going?

849
01:27:43,697 --> 01:27:45,032
To get some friends.

850
01:27:46,700 --> 01:27:48,077
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING)

851
01:28:04,134 --> 01:28:05,761
SOLDIER: All men, stations!

852
01:28:12,810 --> 01:28:14,144
(SHIP WHISTLE BLOWING)

853
01:28:31,912 --> 01:28:32,913
(GUN FIRES)

854
01:28:34,123 --> 01:28:35,416
(ROARING)

855
01:29:02,901 --> 01:29:05,779
It doesn't matter. He's too late.

856
01:29:16,832 --> 01:29:18,375
Move! Move!

857
01:29:18,542 --> 01:29:19,752
Fall back!

858
01:29:28,469 --> 01:29:29,470
(ROARS)

859
01:29:33,307 --> 01:29:34,433
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING)

860
01:29:34,516 --> 01:29:35,642
(MEN SHOUTING)

861
01:29:38,187 --> 01:29:39,188
(RATTLING)

862
01:29:43,609 --> 01:29:45,152
(PANICKED SCREAMING)

863
01:29:46,028 --> 01:29:47,613
Bring her!

864
01:29:47,780 --> 01:29:48,781
(GRUNTING)

865
01:29:59,374 --> 01:30:00,417
(ALL PANTING)

866
01:30:08,634 --> 01:30:10,594
(KUBA SCREAMING)

867
01:30:12,513 --> 01:30:13,555
(SCREAMING)

868
01:30:16,058 --> 01:30:17,101
Grab the diamonds.

869
01:30:18,852 --> 01:30:19,978
Run!

870
01:30:22,272 --> 01:30:25,234
John! No! No! John!

871
01:30:27,569 --> 01:30:28,570
John!

872
01:30:44,378 --> 01:30:45,546
(BRAYS)

873
01:30:53,720 --> 01:30:55,806
Get to the boat! Move!

874
01:30:58,725 --> 01:30:59,726
(SCREAMING)

875
01:31:05,566 --> 01:31:06,567
(YELPS)

876
01:31:07,901 --> 01:31:09,528
We're coming! Hang on!

877
01:31:56,700 --> 01:31:57,868
John?

878
01:32:09,338 --> 01:32:10,756
FRUM: That's the payment.

879
01:32:13,300 --> 01:32:15,469
Lower the skiff, and don't dally.

880
01:32:22,100 --> 01:32:24,770
SOLDIER: Did you see him there?
Is he down there?

881
01:32:31,485 --> 01:32:34,988
1886 model Maxim machine gun.

882
01:32:37,574 --> 01:32:40,285
This is way better than my Walker Colts.

883
01:32:58,220 --> 01:32:59,554
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

884
01:33:04,268 --> 01:33:05,269
(SCREAMS)

885
01:33:13,110 --> 01:33:14,361
(GRUNTING)

886
01:33:50,939 --> 01:33:51,940
(CHOKING)

887
01:34:01,783 --> 01:34:02,826
FRUM: Mr. Rom!

888
01:34:05,746 --> 01:34:07,414
Mr. Frum, you portly coward!

889
01:34:07,581 --> 01:34:09,666
Come and get your diamonds!

890
01:34:14,671 --> 01:34:15,756
(GRUNTING)

891
01:34:16,673 --> 01:34:18,842
Farewell, sweet lord.

892
01:34:21,136 --> 01:34:23,180
Take Tarzan with you.

893
01:34:24,973 --> 01:34:26,850
The future belongs to me.

894
01:34:38,028 --> 01:34:39,279
(GROANING)

895
01:34:40,614 --> 01:34:42,115
(LOW GROWLING)

896
01:34:43,575 --> 01:34:44,785
(LOW GROWLING)

897
01:34:49,831 --> 01:34:50,957
What was that?

898
01:34:53,710 --> 01:34:54,961
Mating call.

899
01:35:02,052 --> 01:35:03,053
(GRUNTING)

900
01:35:28,286 --> 01:35:29,287
(GRUNTS)

901
01:35:29,830 --> 01:35:31,331
(CROCODILES GROWLING)

902
01:35:38,463 --> 01:35:39,464
(GASPING)

903
01:35:42,759 --> 01:35:43,969
Tarzan!

904
01:35:44,636 --> 01:35:46,263
Tarzan!

905
01:35:48,181 --> 01:35:49,057
John!

906
01:35:50,142 --> 01:35:50,976
John!

907
01:35:51,435 --> 01:35:53,812
(ROM SCREAMING)

908
01:35:57,482 --> 01:35:58,483
(HISSING)

909
01:36:26,261 --> 01:36:27,888
(ALL CHEERING)

910
01:36:51,453 --> 01:36:53,413
(ALL CHANTING)

911
01:36:55,790 --> 01:36:57,542
(CHEERING CONTINUES)

912
01:37:01,922 --> 01:37:02,923
(FRUM PANTING)

913
01:37:05,383 --> 01:37:06,843
(ALL ULULATING)

914
01:37:10,096 --> 01:37:12,265
We're not going to wade
into that mess for free.

915
01:37:15,227 --> 01:37:16,561
Raise the anchor!

916
01:38:00,647 --> 01:38:02,566
Ain't this a hell of a thing?

917
01:38:13,326 --> 01:38:14,828
- Nice outfit there, Janey.
- (CHUCKLES)

918
01:38:18,206 --> 01:38:20,208
You looked like
you're about to give me a hug.

919
01:38:21,668 --> 01:38:23,253
No, I wasn't.

920
01:38:24,504 --> 01:38:26,256
Looked like you were.

921
01:38:27,007 --> 01:38:28,592
(LAUGHING)

922
01:38:33,263 --> 01:38:34,764
(TRIBES CHEERING)

923
01:38:52,324 --> 01:38:54,618
GEORGE: An open letter
to His Serene Majesty,

924
01:38:54,784 --> 01:38:59,247
Leopold II, King of the Belgians.

925
01:38:59,414 --> 01:39:00,999
Every charge I'm about to bring

926
01:39:01,166 --> 01:39:03,543
against your Majesty's
personal government of the Congo

927
01:39:03,710 --> 01:39:06,129
has been carefully investigated.

928
01:39:06,296 --> 01:39:11,176
We have witnesses, documents,
letters, and official records

929
01:39:11,343 --> 01:39:14,971
to bring to your attention
and to verify our claims

930
01:39:15,138 --> 01:39:20,560
of your systematic abuse
and enslavement of the Congolese people.

931
01:39:23,063 --> 01:39:27,901
George Washington Williams.
July 18th, 1890.

932
01:40:06,898 --> 01:40:08,650
(KUBA WOMEN SINGING IN OTHER LANGUAGE)

933
01:40:39,389 --> 01:40:42,100
JANE: They are singing
the legend of Tarzan.

934
01:40:49,524 --> 01:40:52,819
For many moons,
he was thought to be an evil spirit.

935
01:40:54,446 --> 01:40:56,239
A ghost in the trees.

936
01:41:02,662 --> 01:41:06,499
They speak of his power
over the animals of the jungle.

937
01:41:08,209 --> 01:41:10,670
Because his spirit came from them.

938
01:41:13,840 --> 01:41:15,467
He understood them,

939
01:41:23,850 --> 01:41:26,352
and learned to be as one with them.

940
01:49:55,569 --> 01:49:56,570
English - SDH
